unk. After concatenating them, the result should equal the sorted array.\nReturn the largest number of chunks we can make to sort the array.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: arr = [5,4,3,2,1]\nOutput: 1\nExplanation:\nSplitting into two or more chunks will not return the required result.\nFor example, splitting into [5, 4], [3, 2, 1] will result in [4, 5, 1, 2, 3], which isn't sorted.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: arr = [2,1,3,4,4]\nOutput: 4\nExplanation:\nWe can split into two chunks, such as [2, 1], [3, 4, 4].\nHowever, splitting into [2, 1], [3], [4], [4] is the highest number of chunks possible.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= arr.length <= 2000\n0 <= arr[i] <= 108\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maxChunksToSorted(self, arr: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def maxChunksToSorted(self, arr: List[int]) -> int:\n        max_so_far = float('-inf')\n        chunks = 0\n        \n        for i in range(len(arr)):\n            max_so_far = max(max_so_far, arr[i])\n            if max_so_far <= min(arr[i+1:]) if i+1 < len(arr) else True:\n                chunks += 1\n        \n        return chunks\n```\n\nThis solution iterates through the array and keeps track of the maximum value encountered so far (`max_so_far`). For each position `i`, it checks if `max_so_far` is less than or equal to the minimum value in the remaining part of the array (`arr[i+1:]`). If this condition is met, it means the array can be split into a chunk up to this point. The function returns the total number of such chunks.\n\nHowever, the above solution has a time complexity of O(n^2) due to the `min(arr[i+1:])` operation. We can optimize it to O(n) by using an auxiliary array to store the minimum values from the end of the array to the current position. Here's the optimized solution:\n\n```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def maxChunksToSorted(self, arr: List[int]) -> int:\n        n = len(arr)\n        min_from_right = [float('inf')] * n\n        min_from_right[-1] = arr[-1]\n        \n        # Fill min_from_right array\n        for i in range(n-2, -1, -1):\n            min_from_right[i] = min(min_from_right[i+1], arr[i])\n        \n        max_so_far = float('-inf')\n        chunks = 0\n        \n        for i in range(n-1):\n            max_so_far = max(max_so_far, arr[i])\n            if max_so_far <= min_from_right[i+1]:\n                chunks += 1\n        \n        # The last chunk is always possible\n        return chunks + 1\n```\n\nIn this optimized version, we first create an array `min_from_right` where `min_from_right[i]` is the minimum value from `arr[i]` to the end of the array. Then, we iterate through the array and use this precomputed array to check the condition for forming chunks, achieving a time complexity of O(n).", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}